Text: When I was in Iraq, the race, religion, or sexual orientation of my fellow Marines didn’t matter. But “Don’t Ask, Don’t Tell” discriminated against some of the bravest Americans I’ve ever met, forcing them to choose between service & being open about who they are.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: I was proud to support President Barack Obama when he repealed the discriminatory policy in 2010. But the repeal didn't include retroactive upgrades for the more than 100,000 service members who had been less-than-honorably discharged since World War II because of who they are.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text:
That’s wrong, and it has real consequences: 
— Anything other than an honorable discharge makes a veteran ineligible for GI Bill benefits & can negatively affect a veteran’s ability to receive health benefits & disability claims.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text:
— An other-than-honorable discharge can negatively affect a veteran’s employment prospects. 
— Veterans who receive something other than an honorable discharge are five to seven times more likely to fall into homelessness.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: Since the repeal of DADT, servicemembers have been able to appeal their discharge status—but the burden of initiating that review rests with the veteran. That burden should be on the government. As President, I’m going to fix this injustice for good.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: The military record correction & discharge review boards will examine the discharge status to determine who was separated for sexual orientation. Unless the military provides records to justify the discharge on other grounds, each veteran’s status will be upgraded to honorable.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: The review boards will then ensure upgraded veterans understand their new benefits, and in the case of deceased veterans, the military records of individual servicemembers will be updated to reflect the change to honorable discharge.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: For too long, our country has discriminated against LGBTQ veterans who put their lives on the line for our freedom. It’s time to fix this injustice for good, and that’s exactly what I will do as President.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: It takes a lot of courage to go to war. It takes even more when you have to hide part of who you are. Text:
During my tours in Iraq, the Marines I led asked me a lot of questions, from big things like what rocket to use to small things like how to send a postcard to their family. 

But there was one question that was the hardest: “Sir, why the hell are we risking our lives for this?"
Name: Seth Moulton

Text:
Many Americans are asking a similar question: what does it mean to fight for a country that lets you down? A country whose leaders let you down? The answer today is the same as it was then: we’re fighting to uphold the values our leaders abandoned.

We’re fighting for who we are.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: True justice means we don’t have a racist criminal justice system that kills & imprisons black Americans for doing the same things white Americans do every day.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: And true justice means we need to start impeachment proceedings against Donald Trump, because neither power nor wealth nor skin color nor office should place anyone above the law.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text:
All of us paid more in taxes than Amazon and Netflix COMBINED—and more than Trump has paid in the last 30 years. That’s not capitalism, that’s crony capitalism. That’s not opportunity, it’s oppression. 

We need a tax code—and a country—that rewards hard work, not tax evasion.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text:
In the greatest democracy in the world, we shouldn’t have voter suppression, the filibuster, gerrymandering, or the electoral college to tell people their votes don’t count. 

It’s time for DC and Puerto Rico to be states, and it’s time for a New Voting Rights Act in America.
Name: Seth Moulton

Text: It’s when our country lets us down the most that we need to work the hardest—it’s when our values are under assault that we need to fight for them.
